Here's a C++ function that takes a reference to a `std::string` containing Markdown formatted text and returns a `std::string` containing HTML formatted text using the `markdown` and `html` libraries:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include "markdown.hpp"
#include "html.hpp"

std::string convertMarkdownToHtml(const std::string& markdownText, const std::string& markdownFilename) {
    std::ifstream markdownFile(markdownFilename);
    if (!markdownFile) {
        std::cerr << "Failed to open Markdown file: " << markdownFilename << std::endl;
        return "";
    }

    markdown_parser_t* parser = markdown_new_parser();
    markdown_parse_string(parser, markdownText.c_str());
    markdown_parser_status_t status = markdown_parser_get_status(parser);
    if (status != MARKDOWN_PARSER_OK) {
        std::cerr << "Failed to parse Markdown: " << markdown_get_error(parser) << std::endl;
        return "";
    }

    std::string htmlText;
    markdown_render(parser, &htmlText);
    markdown_free(parser);

    return htmlText;
}

int main() {
    const std::string markdownText = R"(
        # Header 1
        ## Header 2
        ### Header 3

        This is some **bold** text. *This is some italic* text too. 

        [Link](https://example.com) 

        *List item 1*
        *List item 2*
         ----------
)";

    const std::string markdownFilename = "example.md";
    const std::string htmlText = convertMarkdownToHtml(markdownText, markdownFilename);
    if (htmlText.empty()) {
        std::cerr << "Failed to convert Markdown to HTML" << std::endl;
        return 1;
    }

    std::cout << htmlText << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, we use the `markdown` and `html` libraries, which are available through the header files `markdown.hpp` and `html.hpp`. The `convertMarkdownToHtml` function takes a reference to the Markdown text and the path to the Markdown file as arguments. It reads the contents of the Markdown file, parses it using the `markdown_parse_string` function, renders the parsed HTML using `markdown_render`, and returns the resulting HTML text. In the `main` function, we test the function with a simple Markdown file and print its corresponding HTML output. Make sure to include the necessary header files in your project and adjust the paths to the Markdown and HTML files according to your project requirements.

